name: 1-Iodo-3-nitrobenzene
Reason: The melting point of a compound depends on various factors such as molecular weight, polarity, the presence of hydrogen bonding, and molecular symmetry. In the case of 1-Iodo-3-nitrobenzene, we compare it with benzene as the basic unit: - Benzene has a basic melting point of 5.5 degrees Celsius. - The iodine substituent is a heavy halogen which tends to increase the melting point significantly due to the increase in molecular weight and van der Waals forces. The expected increase could be around +70 degrees Celsius. - The nitro group is an electron-withdrawing group and increases the polarity of the molecule, which can further increase the melting point due to stronger dipole-dipole interactions. However, this effect is less pronounced in the melting point than in the boiling point, the estimated increase could be around +10 degrees Celsius. Considering both substituents and their collective influence on the melting point, we would sum their effects.
